It supports success, error, and informational alerts with optional auto-dismiss functionality.

Each alert is visually distinct, can display lists of success and error messages, and includes a close button for manual dismissal.

Developers can easily integrate it into their projects to provide feedback to users. Alerts are positioned at the bottom of the page and have adjustable opacity for a non-intrusive user experience.

#### 1. Show success, error, and info alerts

Use the library to show alerts of different types by calling:
- `draw_success_alert(title, success_lines, error_lines, remove_seconds)`
- `draw_error_alert(title, success_lines, error_lines, remove_seconds)`
- `draw_info_alert(title, success_lines, error_lines, remove_seconds)`

#### 2. Add a list of success points

The `success_lines` parameter accepts an array of strings representing positive feedback messages.

Example:
```javascript
draw_success_alert('Success!', ['Task completed', 'All checks passed']);
```

#### 3. Add a list of error points

The `error_lines` parameter accepts an array of strings representing error feedback messages.

Example:
```javascript
draw_error_alert('Error!', [], ['An error occurred', 'Retry required']);
```

#### 4. Disappearing Alerts Automatically

The `remove_seconds` parameter defines how long (in seconds) the alert will stay visible before automatically disappearing. Set `-1` to disable auto-dismiss.

Example:
```javascript
draw_info_alert('Info!', ['This is a test message'], [], 5);
```

#### 5. Closing Alerts Manually

You can close the alerts with the cross-icon in the top-right corner of the alert, or you can press `escape` in your keyboard.

#### 6. Close All alerts

If you call the `draw_foo_alert` many time, then many alerts will be opened, one over other.

You can close all together.

```JavaScript
close_alerts();
```





